Author-Name: Matias Iaryczower  
Author-Name: Matthew Shum  
Title: The Value of Information in the Court: Get It Right, Keep It Tight 
Abstract:
 We estimate an equilibrium model of decision making in the US Supreme
 Court that takes into account both private information and ideological
 differences between justices. We measure the value  of information in the
 court by the probability that a justice votes differently from how she
 would have voted without case-specific information. Our results suggest a
 sizable value of information: in 44 percent of cases, justices' initial
 leanings are changed by their personal assessments of the case. Our
 results also confirm the increased politicization of the Supreme Court in
 the last quarter century. Counterfactual simulations provide implications
 for institutional design. (JEL D72, D82, D83, K10)
