Author-Name: Martin Ravallion  
Title: Why Don't We See Poverty Convergence? 
Abstract:
 Average living standards are converging among developing countries and
 faster growing economies see more progress against poverty. Yet we do not
 find poverty convergence; countries starting with higher poverty rates do
 not see higher proportionate rates of poverty reduction. The paper tries
 to explain why. Analysis of a new dataset suggests that, at given mean
 consumption, high initial poverty has an adverse effect on  consumption
 growth and also makes growth less poverty-reducing. Thus, for many poor
 countries, the growth advantage of starting out with a low mean is lost
 due to a high incidence of poverty. (JEL D63, I31, I32, O15)  
